title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,\ell )]]></fr:tex> is constructible, its distance from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,0)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ell ]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ell ]]></fr:tex> is constructible.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longrightarrow )]]></fr:tex> Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ell ]]></fr:tex> is a constructible length. Then there exists points <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P\in  S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q\in  S]]></fr:tex> which has length <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ell ]]></fr:tex>. We will prove <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,\ell )]]></fr:tex> is constructible. There are three possible cases: (1) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ]]></fr:tex> does not pass through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex>, (2) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex> is either <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex>, (3) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex> are distinct points lying on the same line.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Case 1:</fr:strong> Suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ]]></fr:tex> does not pass through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex>. Draw the line parallel to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[OP]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex>, and draw the line parallel to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be the intersection of these two lines. Then we have a parallelogram <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[OPQR]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[OR]]></fr:tex> has the same length as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ]]></fr:tex>. Draw a circle centered at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>, and then we see the circle intersects the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>-axis at the point <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,\ell )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Case 2:</fr:strong> Suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex> is either <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex>. Then drawing a circle at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex> passing through the other point will intersect the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>-axis as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,\ell )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Case 3:</fr:strong> Suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex> are three distinct points lying on the same line <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>. Draw a line <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{2}]]></fr:tex> perpendicular to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>. Draw a circle <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C(P,Q)]]></fr:tex> centered at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q'\in  L_{2}\cap  C(P,Q)]]></fr:tex> be the intersection of the perpendicular line at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> with the circle we just constructed. We can draw a line <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{1}]]></fr:tex> which is perpendicular to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex>, which is parallel to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{2}]]></fr:tex>. We draw a line parallel to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q']]></fr:tex> which intersects <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{1}]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P']]></fr:tex>. Draw a circle centered at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P']]></fr:tex>. Since the length of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[OP']]></fr:tex> is the same as the length of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ']]></fr:tex> (which is the same as the length of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ]]></fr:tex>, i.e., it's the same as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ell ]]></fr:tex>), drawing a circle at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[O]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P']]></fr:tex> will intersect the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>-axis at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,\ell )]]></fr:tex>, as desired.</fr:p><html:span
